import java.util.ListResourceBundle;			      |	public class XSLTErrorResources_zh_CN extends XSLTErrorResour
import java.util.Locale;				      <
import java.util.MissingResourceException;		      <
import java.util.ResourceBundle;			      <
							      <
/**							      <
 * Set up error messages.				      <
 * We build a two dimensional array of message keys and	      <
 * message strings. In order to add a new message here,	      <
 * you need to first add a String constant. And		      <
 *  you need to enter key , value pair as part of contents    <
 * Array. You also need to update MAX_CODE for error strings  <
 * and MAX_WARNING for warnings ( Needed for only information <
 * purpose )						      <
 */							      <
public class XSLTErrorResources_zh_CN extends ListResourceBun <
{							      <
							      <
/*							      <
 * This file contains error and warning messages related to X <
 * Handling.						      <
 *							      <
 *  General notes to translators:			      <
 *							      <
 *  1) Xalan (or more properly, Xalan-interpretive) and XSLTC <
 *     components.					      <
 *     XSLT is an acronym for "XML Stylesheet Language: Trans <
 *     XSLTC is an acronym for XSLT Compiler.		      <
 *							      <
 *  2) A stylesheet is a description of how to transform an i <
 *     into a resultant XML document (or HTML document or tex <
 *     stylesheet itself is described in the form of an XML d <
 *							      <
 *  3) A template is a component of a stylesheet that is used <
 *     particular portion of an input document and specifies  <
 *     corresponding portion of the output document.	      <
 *							      <
 *  4) An element is a mark-up tag in an XML document; an att <
 *     modifier on the tag.  For example, in <elem attr='val' <
 *     "elem" is an element name, "attr" and "attr2" are attr <
 *     the values "val" and "val2", respectively.	      <
 *							      <
 *  5) A namespace declaration is a special attribute that is <
 *     a prefix with a URI (the namespace).  The meanings of  <
 *     attribute names that use that prefix are defined with  <
 *     namespace.					      <
 *							      <
 *  6) "Translet" is an invented term that describes the clas <
 *     results from compiling an XML stylesheet into a Java c <
 *							      <
 *  7) XPath is a specification that describes a notation for <
 *     nodes in a tree-structured representation of an XML do <
 *     instance of that notation is referred to as an XPath e <
 *							      <
 */							      <
							      <
  /** Maximum error messages, this is needed to keep track of <

  // ================= INFRASTRUCTURE ======================  <
							      <
  /** String for use when a bad error code was encountered.   <
  public static final String BAD_CODE = "BAD_CODE";	      <
							      <
  /** String for use when formatting of the error string fail <
  public static final String FORMAT_FAILED = "FORMAT_FAILED"; <
							      <
  /** General error string.   */			      <
  public static final String ERROR_STRING = "#\u9519\u8bef";  <
							      <
  /** String to prepend to error messages.  */		      <
  public static final String ERROR_HEADER = "\u9519\u8bef:";  <
							      <
  /** String to prepend to warning messages.    */	      <
  public static final String WARNING_HEADER = "\u8b66\u544a:" <
							      <
  /** String to specify the XSLT module.  */		      <
  public static final String XSL_HEADER = "XSLT ";	      <
							      <
  /** String to specify the XML parser module.  */	      <
  public static final String XML_HEADER = "XML ";	      <
							      <
  /** I don't think this is used any more.		      <
   * @deprecated  */					      <
  public static final String QUERY_HEADER = "PATTERN ";	      <
							      <
							      <
  /**							      <
   *   Return a named ResourceBundle for a particular locale. <
   *   of ResourceBundle.getBundle().			      <
   *							      <
   *   @param className the name of the class that implements <
   *   @return the ResourceBundle			      <
   *   @throws MissingResourceException			      <
   */							      <
  public static final XSLTErrorResources loadResourceBundle(S <
          throws MissingResourceException		      <
  {							      <
							      <
    Locale locale = Locale.getDefault();		      <
    String suffix = getResourceSuffix(locale);		      <
							      <
    try							      <
    {							      <
							      <
      // first try with the given locale		      <
      return (XSLTErrorResources) ResourceBundle.getBundle(cl <
              + suffix, locale);			      <
    }							      <
    catch (MissingResourceException e)			      <
    {							      <
      try  // try to fall back to en_US if we can't load      <
      {							      <
							      <
        // Since we can't find the localized property file,   <
        // fall back to en_US.				      <
        return (XSLTErrorResources) ResourceBundle.getBundle( <
                new Locale("zh", "CN"));		      <
      }							      <
      catch (MissingResourceException e2)		      <
      {							      <
							      <
        // Now we are really in trouble.		      <
        // very bad, definitely very bad...not going to get v <
        throw new MissingResourceException(		      <
          "\u65e0\u6cd5\u88c5\u5165\u4efb\u4f55\u8d44\u6e90\u <
      }							      <
    }							      <
  }							      <
							      <
  /**							      <
   * Return the resource file suffic for the indicated locale <
   * For most locales, this will be based the language code.  <
   * for Chinese, we do distinguish between Taiwan and PRC    <
   *							      <
   * @param locale the locale				      <
   * @return an String suffix which canbe appended to a resou <
   */							      <
  private static final String getResourceSuffix(Locale locale <
  {							      <
							      <
    String suffix = "_" + locale.getLanguage();		      <
    String country = locale.getCountry();		      <
							      <
    if (country.equals("TW"))				      <
      suffix += "_" + country;				      <
							      <
    return suffix;					      <
  }							      <

import java.net.URL;					      <
import java.net.MalformedURLException;			      <
							      <
							      >	    private Vector _elementsWithNamespacesUsedDynamically = n
							      >
							      >	     * @see XSLTC#_templateInlining
    private boolean _templateInlining = true;		      |	    private boolean _templateInlining = false;
		    _hasLocalParams = new Boolean(true);      |			    _hasLocalParams = Boolean.TRUE;
	    _hasLocalParams = new Boolean(false);	      |		    _hasLocalParams = Boolean.FALSE;
     * Compile the namesArray, urisArray and typesArray into  |	     * <p>Compile the namesArray, urisArray, typesArray, name
							      >	     * namespaceAncestorsArray, prefixURIsIdxArray and prefix
     * copy of this informtion.				      |	     * copy of this informtion.</p>
							      >	     * <p>The <code>namespaceAncestorsArray</code>,
							      >	     * <code>prefixURIsIdxArray</code> and <code>prefixURIPai
							      >	     * contain namespace information accessible from the styl
							      >	     * <dl>
							      >	     * <dt><code>namespaceAncestorsArray</code></dt>
							      >	     * <dd>Array indexed by integer stylesheet node IDs conta
							      >	     * the nearest ancestor node in the stylesheet with names
							      >	     * declarations or <code>-1</code> if there is no such an
							      >	     * can be more than one disjoint tree of nodes - one for 
							      >	     * module</dd>
							      >	     * <dt><code>prefixURIsIdxArray</code></dt>
							      >	     * <dd>Array indexed by integer stylesheet node IDs conta
							      >	     * into <code>prefixURIPairsArray</code> of the first nam
							      >	     * declared for the node.  The values are stored in ascen
							      >	     * the next value in this array (if any) can be used to f
							      >	     * prefix-URI pair</dd>
							      >	     * <dt>prefixURIPairsArray</dt>
							      >	     * <dd>Array of pairs of namespace prefixes and URIs.  A 
							      >	     * string represents the default namespace if it appears 
							      >	     * a namespace undeclaration if it appears as a URI.</dd>
							      >	     * </dl>
							      >	     * </p>
							      >	     * <p>For this stylesheet
							      >	     * <pre><code>
							      >	     * &lt;xsl:stylesheet xmlns:xsl="http://www.w3.org/1999/X
							      >	     *   &lt;xsl:template match="/"&gt;
							      >	     *     &lt;xsl:for-each select="*" xmlns:foo="foouri"&gt;
							      >	     *       &lt;xsl:element name="{n}" xmlns:foo="baruri"&gt
							      >	     *     &lt;/xsl:for-each&gt;
							      >	     *     &lt;out xmlns="lumpit"/&gt;
							      >	     *     &lt;xsl:element name="{n}" xmlns="foouri"/&gt;
							      >	     *     &lt;xsl:element name="{n}" namespace="{ns}" xmlns=
							      >	     *   &lt;/xsl:template&gt;
							      >	     * &lt;/xsl:stylesheet&gt;
							      >	     * </code></pre>
							      >	     * there will be four stylesheet nodes whose namespace in
							      >	     * needed, and
							      >	     * <ul>
							      >	     * <li><code>namespaceAncestorsArray</code> will have the
							      >	     * <code>[-1,0,1,0]</code>;</li>

							      >	        int[] adjacencyRunStart = new int[chunks.length];

							      >	    /**
							      >	     * <p>Get all {@link Method}s generated by this {@link Me

							      >	     * exceed the 64KB limit, this method will attempt to spl
							      >	     * the {@link InstructionList} associated with this
							      >	     * <code>MethodGenerator</code> into several methods.</p>
							      >	     * @param classGen the {@link ClassGenerator} of which th
							      >	     *                 members

							      >	     */

							      >	        Method[] generatedMethods;
							      >	        InstructionList il = getInstructionList();
							      >	        InstructionHandle last = il.getEnd();
							      >

							      >	                    last.getPosition() + last.getInstruction(
							      >

							      >	        // [-32768,32767]

							      >	            boolean ilChanged = widenConditionalBranchTargetO
							      >

							      >	            // of the byte code for the method

							      >	    protected Method getThisMethod() {
							      >	        stripAttributes(true);
							      >	        setMaxLocals();
							      >	        setMaxStack();
							      >	        removeNOPs();
							      >

							      >	    /**
							      >	     * <p>Rewrites branches to avoid the JVM limits of relati
							      >	     * offsets.  There is no need to invoke this method if th
							      >	     * {@link MethodGenerator} does not exceed 32KB.</p>
							      >	     * <p>The Java Virtual Machine Specification permits the 
							      >	     * method to be up to 64KB in length.  However, some cont
							      >	     * instructions specify relative offsets as a signed 16-b
							      >	     * limiting the range to a subset of the instructions tha
							      >	     * method.</p>
							      >	     * <p>The <code>TABLESWITCH</code> and <code>LOOKUPSWITCH
							      >	     * instructions always use 32-bit signed relative offsets
							      >	     * immune to this problem.</p>
							      >	     * <p>The <code>GOTO</code> and <code>JSR</code>
							      >	     * instructions come in two forms, one of which uses 16-b
							      >	     * offsets, and the other of which uses 32-bit relative o
							      >	     * library decides whether to use the wide form of <code>
							      >	     * <code>JSR</code>instructions based on the relative off
							      >	     * of the instruction without any intervention by the use
							      >	     * library.</p>
							      >	     * <p>This leaves the various conditional branch instruct
							      >	     * <code>IFEQ</code>, <code>IFNULL</code>, <code>IF_ICMPE
							      >	     * <em>et al.</em>, all of which use 16-bit signed relati
							      >	     * 32-bit wide form available.</p>
							      >	     * <p>This method scans the {@link InstructionList} assoc
							      >	     * {@link MethodGenerator} and finds all conditional bran
							      >	     * that might exceed the 16-bit limitation for relative b
							      >	     * The logic of each such instruction is inverted, and ma
							      >	     * instruction which follows it.  An unconditional branch
							      >	     * target of the instruction is then inserted between the
							      >	     * branch and the instruction which previously followed i
							      >	     * unconditional branch is permitted to have a 16-bit or 
							      >	     * offset, as described above.  For example,
							      >	     * <code>
							      >	     * 1234:   NOP
							      >	     *          ...
							      >	     * 55278:  IFEQ -54044
							      >	     * 55280:  NOP
							      >	     * </code>
							      >	     * is rewritten as
							      >	     * <code>
							      >	     * 1234:   NOP
							      >	     *          ...
							      >	     * 55278:  IFNE 7
							      >	     * 55280:  GOTO_W -54046
							      >	     * 55285:  NOP
							      >	     * </code></p>
							      >	     * <p><b>Preconditions:</b>
							      >	     * <ul><li>The {@link InstructionList#setPositions()} has
							      >	     * the <code>InstructionList</code> associated with this
							      >	     * <code>MethodGenerator</code>.
							      >	     * </li></ul></p>
							      >	     * <p><b>Postconditions:</b>
							      >	     * <ul><li>Any further changes to the <code>InstructionLi
							      >	     * <code>MethodGenerator</code> will invalidate the chang
							      >	     * method.</li></ul>
							      >	     * </p>
							      >	     * @return <code>true</code> if the <code>InstructionList
							      >	     * modified; <code>false</code> otherwise
							      >	     * @see The Java Virtual Machine Specification, Second Ed
							      >	     */
							      >	    boolean widenConditionalBranchTargetOffsets() {
							      >	        boolean ilChanged = false;
							      >	        int maxOffsetChange = 0;
							      >	        InstructionList il = getInstructionList();
							      >
							      >	        // Loop through all the instructions, finding those t
							      >	        // affected by inserting new instructions in the Inst
							      >	        // calculating the maximum amount by which the relati
							      >	        // two instructions could possibly change.
							      >	        // In part this loop duplicates code in
							      >	        // org.apache.bcel.generic.InstructionList.setPositio
							      >	        // this to determine whether to use 16-bit or 32-bit 
							      >	        // and JSR instructions.  Ideally, that method would 
							      >	        // conditional branch instructions, but it doesn't, s
							      >	        // processing here.
							      >	        for (InstructionHandle ih = il.getStart();
							      >	             ih != null;
							      >	             ih = ih.getNext()) {
							      >	            Instruction inst = ih.getInstruction();
							      >	           
							      >	            switch (inst.getOpcode()) {
							      >	                // Instructions that may have 16-bit or 32-bi
							      >	                // The size of the branch offset might increa
							      >	                case Constants.GOTO:
							      >	                case Constants.JSR:
							      >	                    maxOffsetChange = maxOffsetChange + 2; 
							      >	                    break;
							      >	                // Instructions that contain padding for alig
							      >	                // Up to three bytes of padding might be need
							      >	                // accuracy, we should be able to discount an
							      >	                // added to these instructions by Instruction
							      >	                // their APIs do not expose that information.
							      >	                case Constants.TABLESWITCH:
							      >	                case Constants.LOOKUPSWITCH:
							      >	                    maxOffsetChange = maxOffsetChange + 3;
							      >	                    break;
							      >	                // Instructions that might be rewritten by th
							      >	                // conditional branch followed by an uncondit
							      >	                // The unconditional branch would require fiv
							      >	                case Constants.IF_ACMPEQ:
							      >	                case Constants.IF_ACMPNE:
							      >	                case Constants.IF_ICMPEQ:
							      >	                case Constants.IF_ICMPGE:
							      >	                case Constants.IF_ICMPGT:
							      >	                case Constants.IF_ICMPLE:
							      >	                case Constants.IF_ICMPLT:
							      >	                case Constants.IF_ICMPNE:
							      >	                case Constants.IFEQ:
							      >	                case Constants.IFGE:
							      >	                case Constants.IFGT:
							      >	                case Constants.IFLE:
							      >	                case Constants.IFLT:
							      >	                case Constants.IFNE:
							      >	                case Constants.IFNONNULL:
							      >	                case Constants.IFNULL:
							      >	                    maxOffsetChange = maxOffsetChange + 5;
							      >	                    break;
							      >	            }
							      >	        }
							      >
							      >	        // Now that the maximum number of bytes by which the 
							      >	        // has been determined, look for conditional branches
							      >	        // might possibly exceed the 16-bit relative offset.
							      >	        for (InstructionHandle ih = il.getStart();
							      >	             ih != null;
							      >	             ih = ih.getNext()) {
							      >	            Instruction inst = ih.getInstruction();
							      >
							      >	            if (inst instanceof IfInstruction) {
							      >	                IfInstruction oldIfInst = (IfInstruction)inst
							      >	                BranchHandle oldIfHandle = (BranchHandle)ih;
							      >	                InstructionHandle target = oldIfInst.getTarge
							      >	                int relativeTargetOffset = target.getPosition
							      >	                                               - oldIfHandle.
							      >
							      >	                // Consider the worst case scenario in which 
							      >	                // branch and its target are separated by all
							      >	                // in the method that might increase in size.
							      >	                // in a relative offset that cannot be repres
							      >	                // signed quantity, rewrite the instruction a
							      >	                if ((relativeTargetOffset - maxOffsetChange
							      >	                             < MIN_BRANCH_TARGET_OFFSET)
							      >	                        || (relativeTargetOffset + maxOffsetC
							      >	                                    > MAX_BRANCH_TARGET_OFFSE
							      >	                    // Invert the logic of the IF instruction
							      >	                    // that to the InstructionList following 
							      >	                    // instruction
							      >	                    InstructionHandle nextHandle = oldIfHandl
							      >	                    IfInstruction invertedIfInst = oldIfInst.
							      >	                    BranchHandle invertedIfHandle = il.append
							      >	                                                             
							      >
							      >	                    // Append an unconditional branch to the 
							      >	                    // original IF instruction after the new 
							      >	                    BranchHandle gotoHandle = il.append(inver
							      >	                                                        new G
							      >
							      >	                    // If the original IF was the last instru
							      >	                    // InstructionList, add a new no-op to ac
							      >	                    // of the new IF
							      >	                    if (nextHandle == null) {
							      >	                        nextHandle = il.append(gotoHandle, NO
							      >	                    }
							      >
							      >	                    // Make the new IF instruction branch aro
							      >	                    invertedIfHandle.updateTarget(target, nex
							      >
							      >	                    // If anything still "points" to the old 
							      >	                    // make adjustments to refer to either th
							      >	                    // instruction
							      >	                    if (oldIfHandle.hasTargeters()) {
							      >	                        InstructionTargeter[] targeters =
							      >	                                                  oldIfHandle
							      >

							      >	                            InstructionTargeter targeter = ta
							      >	                            // Ideally, one should simply be 
							      >	                            // InstructionTargeter.updateTarg
							      >	                            // references to the old IF instr

							      >	                            // indicated the old IF marked th

							      >	                            // newly created GOTO instruction

    private void heapify(int i) {			      <

							      >	     * are in the encoding. Characters with higher code point
							      >	     * in the encoding. A value of zero is returned if the hi
							      >	     * <p>
							      >	     * This method is not a public API.
							      >	     * @xsl.usage internal
							      >	     */
							      >	    static public char getHighChar(String encoding)
							      >	    {
							      >	        final char highCodePoint;

							      >	        else
							      >	            highCodePoint = 0;
							      >	        return highCodePoint;

############################################################# |	##
							      >	#
							      >	# $Id$
							      >	#
							      >	# Each entry in this properties file is:
							      >	# 1) The Java name for the encoding
							      >	# 2) A comma separated list of the MIME names for the encodin
							      >	#    with the first one being the preferred MIME name.
							      >	# 3) An optional high char. Characters at or below this value
							      >	#    definately in the encoding, but characters above it may 
							      >	#    This value is given only for performance reasons.
							      >	#    A value of zero is the same as no value at all.
							      >	#
							      >	# For example this line in this file:
							      >	#              ASCII ASCII,US-ASCII 0x007F
							      >	# Means the Java name for the encoding is "ASCII". The MIME n
							      >	# encoding which may appear in a stylesheet are "ASCII" or "U
							      >	# and the optional high code point value is given, and it is 
							      >	# which means that the contiguous block of chars from
							      >	# 0x0001 to 0x007F ( 127 in base 10) are all in the encoding.
							      >	# Higher values above this char might be in the encoding, alt
							      >	# case of this particular encoding there are no higher chars.

     * Flush any pending events currently queued up in the se |	     * A SerializationHandler accepts SAX-like events, so
     * flush any input that the serializer has which it has n |	     * it can accumulate attributes or namespace nodes after

							      >	     * events as a SAX (not SAX-like) calls to

							      |	import java.util.Locale;
							      >	import java.util.MissingResourceException;
							      >	import java.util.ResourceBundle;
							      >
							      >	/**
							      >	 * An instance of this class is a ListResourceBundle that
							      >	 * has the required getContents() method that returns
							      >	 * an array of message-key/message associations.
							      >	 * <p>
							      >	 * The message keys are defined in {@link MsgKey}. The
							      >	 * messages that those keys map to are defined here.
							      >	 * <p>
							      >	 * The messages in the English version are intended to be
							      >	 * translated.
							      >	 *
							      >	 * This class is not a public API, it is only public because 
							      >	 * used in org.apache.xml.serializer.
							      >	 *
							      >	 * @xsl.usage internal
							      >	 */
							      >
							      >	    /*
							      >	     * This file contains error and warning messages related 
							      >	     * Serializer Error Handling.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  General notes to translators:
							      >
							      >	     *  1) A stylesheet is a description of how to transform 
							      >	     *     into a resultant XML document (or HTML document or
							      >	     *     stylesheet itself is described in the form of an X
							      >
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  2) An element is a mark-up tag in an XML document; an
							      >	     *     modifier on the tag.  For example, in <elem attr='
							      >	     *     "elem" is an element name, "attr" and "attr2" are 
							      >	     *     the values "val" and "val2", respectively.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  3) A namespace declaration is a special attribute tha
							      >	     *     a prefix with a URI (the namespace).  The meanings
							      >	     *     attribute names that use that prefix are defined w
							      >	     *     namespace.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *
							      >	     */
							      >
							      >	    /** The lookup table for error messages.   */

							      >	     * This file contains error and warning messages related 
							      >	     * Serializer Error Handling.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  General notes to translators:
							      >
							      >	     *  1) A stylesheet is a description of how to transform 
							      >	     *     into a resultant XML document (or HTML document or
							      >	     *     stylesheet itself is described in the form of an X
							      >
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  2) An element is a mark-up tag in an XML document; an
							      >	     *     modifier on the tag.  For example, in <elem attr='
							      >	     *     "elem" is an element name, "attr" and "attr2" are 
							      >	     *     the values "val" and "val2", respectively.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  3) A namespace declaration is a special attribute tha
							      >	     *     a prefix with a URI (the namespace).  The meanings
							      >	     *     attribute names that use that prefix are defined w
							      >	     *     namespace.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *
							      >	     */
							      >

							      >	/**
							      >	 * An instance of this class is a ListResourceBundle that
							      >	 * has the required getContents() method that returns
							      >	 * an array of message-key/message associations.
							      >	 * <p>
							      >	 * The message keys are defined in {@link MsgKey}. The
							      >	 * messages that those keys map to are defined here.
							      >	 * <p>
							      >	 * The messages in the English version are intended to be
							      >	 * translated.
							      >	 *
							      >	 * This class is not a public API, it is only public because 
							      >	 * used in org.apache.xml.serializer.
							      >	 *
							      >	 * @xsl.usage internal
							      >	 */
							      >
							      >	    /*
							      >	     * This file contains error and warning messages related 
							      >	     * Serializer Error Handling.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  General notes to translators:
							      >
							      >	     *  1) A stylesheet is a description of how to transform 
							      >	     *     into a resultant XML document (or HTML document or
							      >	     *     stylesheet itself is described in the form of an X
							      >
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  2) An element is a mark-up tag in an XML document; an
							      >	     *     modifier on the tag.  For example, in <elem attr='
							      >	     *     "elem" is an element name, "attr" and "attr2" are 
							      >	     *     the values "val" and "val2", respectively.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  3) A namespace declaration is a special attribute tha
							      >	     *     a prefix with a URI (the namespace).  The meanings
							      >	     *     attribute names that use that prefix are defined w
							      >	     *     namespace.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *
							      >	     */
							      >

							      >	/**
							      >	 * An instance of this class is a ListResourceBundle that
							      >	 * has the required getContents() method that returns
							      >	 * an array of message-key/message associations.
							      >	 * <p>
							      >	 * The message keys are defined in {@link MsgKey}. The
							      >	 * messages that those keys map to are defined here.
							      >	 * <p>
							      >	 * The messages in the English version are intended to be
							      >	 * translated.
							      >	 *
							      >	 * This class is not a public API, it is only public because 
							      >	 * used in org.apache.xml.serializer.
							      >	 *
							      >	 * @xsl.usage internal
							      >	 */
							      >
							      >	    /*
							      >	     * This file contains error and warning messages related 
							      >	     * Serializer Error Handling.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  General notes to translators:
							      >
							      >	     *  1) A stylesheet is a description of how to transform 
							      >	     *     into a resultant XML document (or HTML document or
							      >	     *     stylesheet itself is described in the form of an X
							      >
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  2) An element is a mark-up tag in an XML document; an
							      >	     *     modifier on the tag.  For example, in <elem attr='
							      >	     *     "elem" is an element name, "attr" and "attr2" are 
							      >	     *     the values "val" and "val2", respectively.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  3) A namespace declaration is a special attribute tha
							      >	     *     a prefix with a URI (the namespace).  The meanings
							      >	     *     attribute names that use that prefix are defined w
							      >	     *     namespace.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *
							      >	     */
							      >
							      >	    /** The lookup table for error messages.   */

							      |	import java.util.Locale;
							      >	import java.util.MissingResourceException;
							      >	import java.util.ResourceBundle;

							      >	/**
							      >	 * An instance of this class is a ListResourceBundle that
							      >	 * has the required getContents() method that returns
							      >	 * an array of message-key/message associations.
							      >	 * <p>
							      >	 * The message keys are defined in {@link MsgKey}. The
							      >	 * messages that those keys map to are defined here.
							      >	 * <p>
							      >	 * The messages in the English version are intended to be
							      >	 * translated.
							      >	 *
							      >	 * This class is not a public API, it is only public because 
							      >	 * used in org.apache.xml.serializer.
							      >	 *
							      >	 * @xsl.usage internal
							      >	 */
							      >
							      >	    /*
							      >	     * This file contains error and warning messages related 
							      >	     * Serializer Error Handling.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  General notes to translators:
							      >
							      >	     *  1) A stylesheet is a description of how to transform 
							      >	     *     into a resultant XML document (or HTML document or
							      >	     *     stylesheet itself is described in the form of an X
							      >
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  2) An element is a mark-up tag in an XML document; an
							      >	     *     modifier on the tag.  For example, in <elem attr='
							      >	     *     "elem" is an element name, "attr" and "attr2" are 
							      >	     *     the values "val" and "val2", respectively.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  3) A namespace declaration is a special attribute tha
							      >	     *     a prefix with a URI (the namespace).  The meanings
							      >	     *     attribute names that use that prefix are defined w
							      >	     *     namespace.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *
							      >	     */
							      >
							      >	    /** The lookup table for error messages.   */

							      >	/**
							      >	 * An instance of this class is a ListResourceBundle that
							      >	 * has the required getContents() method that returns
							      >	 * an array of message-key/message associations.
							      >	 * <p>
							      >	 * The message keys are defined in {@link MsgKey}. The
							      >	 * messages that those keys map to are defined here.
							      >	 * <p>
							      >	 * The messages in the English version are intended to be
							      >	 * translated.
							      >	 *
							      >	 * This class is not a public API, it is only public because 
							      >	 * used in org.apache.xml.serializer.
							      >	 *
							      >	 * @xsl.usage internal
							      >	 */
							      >
							      >	    /*
							      >	     * This file contains error and warning messages related 
							      >	     * Serializer Error Handling.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  General notes to translators:
							      >
							      >	     *  1) A stylesheet is a description of how to transform 
							      >	     *     into a resultant XML document (or HTML document or
							      >	     *     stylesheet itself is described in the form of an X
							      >
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  2) An element is a mark-up tag in an XML document; an
							      >	     *     modifier on the tag.  For example, in <elem attr='
							      >	     *     "elem" is an element name, "attr" and "attr2" are 
							      >	     *     the values "val" and "val2", respectively.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  3) A namespace declaration is a special attribute tha
							      >	     *     a prefix with a URI (the namespace).  The meanings
							      >	     *     attribute names that use that prefix are defined w
							      >	     *     namespace.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *
							      >	     */
							      >
							      >	    /** The lookup table for error messages.   */

							      >	/**
							      >	 * An instance of this class is a ListResourceBundle that
							      >	 * has the required getContents() method that returns
							      >	 * an array of message-key/message associations.
							      >	 * <p>
							      >	 * The message keys are defined in {@link MsgKey}. The
							      >	 * messages that those keys map to are defined here.
							      >	 * <p>
							      >	 * The messages in the English version are intended to be
							      >	 * translated.

							      >	 * This class is not a public API, it is only public because 
							      >	 * used in org.apache.xml.serializer.
							      >	 *
							      >	 * @xsl.usage internal
							      >	 */

							      >	     * This file contains error and warning messages related 
							      >	     * Serializer Error Handling.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  General notes to translators:
							      >
							      >	     *  1) A stylesheet is a description of how to transform 
							      >	     *     into a resultant XML document (or HTML document or
							      >	     *     stylesheet itself is described in the form of an X
							      >
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  2) An element is a mark-up tag in an XML document; an
							      >	     *     modifier on the tag.  For example, in <elem attr='
							      >	     *     "elem" is an element name, "attr" and "attr2" are 
							      >	     *     the values "val" and "val2", respectively.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *  3) A namespace declaration is a special attribute tha
							      >	     *     a prefix with a URI (the namespace).  The meanings
							      >	     *     attribute names that use that prefix are defined w
							      >	     *     namespace.
							      >	     *
							      >	     *
							      >	     */
							      >

							      >	    * It used to be that many locations in the code simply

							      >	    * calling the setObject(Object) method. The problem is
							      >	    * that our super-class would be updated on what the 
							      >	    * cache associated with this NodeSequence, but
							      >	    * we wouldn't know ourselves.
							      >	    * <p>

							      >	    * and this method over-rides the super-class method.
							      >	    * So now we are in the loop have an opportunity

							      >	       }
							      >	       
							      >	   }
							      >
							      >	   /**
							      >	    * Each NodeSequence object has an iterator which is "walk
							      >	    * As an iterator is walked one obtains nodes from it.
							      >	    * As those nodes are obtained they may be cached, making
							      >	    * the next walking of a copy or clone of the iterator fas
							      >	    * This field (m_cache) is a reference to such a cache, 
							      >	    * which is populated as the iterator is walked.
							      >	    * <p>
							      >	    * Note that multiple NodeSequence objects may hold a 
							      >	    * reference to the same cache, and also 
							      >	    * (and this is important) the same iterator.
							      >	    * The iterator and its cache may be shared among 
							      >	    * many NodeSequence objects.
							      >	    * <p>
							      >	    * If one of the NodeSequence objects walks ahead
							      >	    * of the others it fills in the cache.
							      >	    * As the others NodeSequence objects catch up they
							      >	    * get their values from
							      >	    * the cache rather than the iterator itself, so
							      >	    * the iterator is only ever walked once and everyone
							      >	    * benefits from the cache.
							      >	    * <p>
							      >	    * At some point the cache may be
							      >	    * complete due to walking to the end of one of
							      >	    * the copies of the iterator, and the cache is
							      >	    * then marked as "complete".
							      >	    * and the cache will have no more nodes added to it.
							      >	    * <p>
							      >	    * Its use-count is the number of NodeSequence objects tha
							      >	    */
							      >	   private final static class IteratorCache {
							      >	       /**
							      >	        * A list of nodes already obtained from the iterator.
							      >	        * As the iterator is walked the nodes obtained from
							      >	        * it are appended to this list.
							      >	        * <p>
							      >	        * Both an iterator and its corresponding cache can
							      >	        * be shared by multiple NodeSequence objects.
							      >	        * <p>
							      >	        * For example, consider three NodeSequence objects
							      >	        * ns1, ns2 and ns3 doing such sharing, and the
							      >	        * nodes to be obtaind from the iterator being 
							      >	        * the sequence { 33, 11, 44, 22, 55 }.
							      >	        * <p>
							      >	        * If ns3.nextNode() is called 3 times the the
							      >	        * underlying iterator will have walked through
							      >	        * 33, 11, 55 and these three nodes will have been put
							      >	        * in the cache.
							      >	        * <p>
							      >	        * If ns2.nextNode() is called 2 times it will return
							      >	        * 33 and 11 from the cache, leaving the iterator alon
							      >	        * <p>
							      >	        * If ns1.nextNode() is called 6 times it will return
							      >	        * 33 and 11 from the cache, then get 44, 22, 55 from
							      >	        * the iterator, and appending 44, 22, 55 to the cache
							      >	        * On the sixth call it is found that the iterator is
							      >	        * exhausted and the cache is marked complete.
							      >	        * <p>
							      >	        * Should ns2 or ns3 have nextNode() called they will
							      >	        * know that the cache is complete, and they will
							      >	        * obtain all subsequent nodes from the cache.
							      >	        * <p>
							      >	        * Note that the underlying iterator, though shared
							      >	        * is only ever walked once. 
							      >	        */
							      >	        private NodeVector m_vec2;
							      >
							      >	        /**
							      >	         * true if the associated iterator is exhausted and
							      >	         * all nodes obtained from it are in the cache.
							      >	         */
							      >	        private boolean m_isComplete2;
							      >
							      >	        private int m_useCount2;
							      >
							      >	        IteratorCache() {
							      >	            m_vec2 = null;
							      >	            m_isComplete2 = false;
							      >	            m_useCount2 = 1;
							      >	            return;
							      >	        }
							      >
							      >	        /**
							      >	         * Returns count of how many NodeSequence objects sha
							      >	         * IteratorCache object.
							      >	         */
							      >	        private int useCount() {
							      >	            return m_useCount2;
							      >	        }
							      >
							      >	        /**
							      >	         * This method is called when yet another
							      >	         * NodeSequence object uses, or shares
							      >	         * this same cache.
							      >	         *
							      >	         */
							      >	        private void increaseUseCount() {
							      >	            if (m_vec2 != null)
							      >	                m_useCount2++;
							      >
							      >	        }
							      >
							      >	        /**
							      >	         * Sets the NodeVector that holds the
							      >	         * growing list of nodes as they are appended
							      >	         * to the cached list.
							      >	         */
							      >	        private void setVector(NodeVector nv) {
							      >	            m_vec2 = nv;
							      >	            m_useCount2 = 1;
							      >	        }
							      >
							      >	        /**
							      >	         * Get the cached list of nodes obtained from
							      >	         * the iterator so far.
							      >	         */
							      >	        private NodeVector getVector() {
							      >	            return m_vec2;
							      >	        }
							      >
							      >	        /**
							      >	         * Call this method with 'true' if the
							      >	         * iterator is exhausted and the cached list
							      >	         * is complete, or no longer growing.
							      >	         */
							      >	        private void setCacheComplete(boolean b) {
							      >	            m_isComplete2 = b;
							      >
							      >	        }
							      >
							      >	        /**
							      >	         * Returns true if no cache is complete
							      >	         * and immutable.
							      >	         */
							      >	        private boolean isComplete() {
							      >	            return m_isComplete2;
							      >	        }

import java.util.Locale;				      <
import java.util.MissingResourceException;		      <
import java.util.ResourceBundle;			      <
							      <
/**							      <
 * Set up error messages.				      <
 * We build a two dimensional array of message keys and	      <
 * message strings. In order to add a new message here,	      <
 * you need to first add a Static string constant for the     <
 * Key and update the contents array with Key, Value pair     <
  * Also you need to  update the count of messages(MAX_CODE)o <
 * the count of warnings(MAX_WARNING) [ Information purpose o <
 * @xsl.usage advanced					      <
 */							      <
public class XPATHErrorResources_zh_CN extends ListResourceBu <
{							      <
							      <
/*							      <
 * General notes to translators:			      <
 *							      <
 * This file contains error and warning messages related to X <
 * Handling.						      <
 *							      <
 *  1) Xalan (or more properly, Xalan-interpretive) and XSLTC <
 *     components.					      <
 *     XSLT is an acronym for "XML Stylesheet Language: Trans <
 *     XSLTC is an acronym for XSLT Compiler.		      <
 *							      <
 *  2) A stylesheet is a description of how to transform an i <
 *     into a resultant XML document (or HTML document or tex <
 *     stylesheet itself is described in the form of an XML d <
 *							      <
 *  3) A template is a component of a stylesheet that is used <
 *     particular portion of an input document and specifies  <
 *     corresponding portion of the output document.	      <
 *							      <
 *  4) An element is a mark-up tag in an XML document; an att <
 *     modifier on the tag.  For example, in <elem attr='val' <
 *     "elem" is an element name, "attr" and "attr2" are attr <
 *     the values "val" and "val2", respectively.	      <
 *							      <
 *  5) A namespace declaration is a special attribute that is <
 *     a prefix with a URI (the namespace).  The meanings of  <
 *     attribute names that use that prefix are defined with  <
 *     namespace.					      <
 *							      <
 *  6) "Translet" is an invented term that describes the clas <
 *     results from compiling an XML stylesheet into a Java c <
 *							      <
 *  7) XPath is a specification that describes a notation for <
 *     nodes in a tree-structured representation of an XML do <
 *     instance of that notation is referred to as an XPath e <
 *							      <
 *  8) The context node is the node in the document with resp <
 *     XPath expression is being evaluated.		      <
 *							      <
 *  9) An iterator is an object that traverses nodes in the t <
 *							      <
 *  10) NCName is an XML term used to describe a name that do <
 *     colon (a "no-colon name").			      <
 *							      <
 *  11) QName is an XML term meaning "qualified name".	      <
 */							      <
							      <
  /** Field MAX_CODE          */			      <
  public static final int MAX_CODE = 108;  // this is needed  <
							      <
  /** Field MAX_WARNING          */			      <
  public static final int MAX_WARNING = 11;  // this is neede <
							      <
  /** Field MAX_OTHERS          */			      <
  public static final int MAX_OTHERS = 20;		      <
							      <
  /** Field MAX_MESSAGES          */			      <
  public static final int MAX_MESSAGES = MAX_CODE + MAX_WARNI <

  /**							      <
   * Return a named ResourceBundle for a particular locale.   <
   * of ResourceBundle.getBundle().			      <
   *							      <
   * @param className Name of local-specific subclass.	      <
   * @return the ResourceBundle				      <
   * @throws MissingResourceException			      <
   */							      <
  public static final XPATHErrorResources loadResourceBundle( <
          throws MissingResourceException		      <
							      <
    Locale locale = Locale.getDefault();		      <
    String suffix = getResourceSuffix(locale);		      <
							      <
    try							      <
    {							      <
							      <
      // first try with the given locale		      <
      return (XPATHErrorResources) ResourceBundle.getBundle(c <
              + suffix, locale);			      <
    }							      <
    catch (MissingResourceException e)			      <
    {							      <
      try  // try to fall back to en_US if we can't load      <
      {							      <
							      <
        // Since we can't find the localized property file,   <
        // fall back to en_US.				      <
        return (XPATHErrorResources) ResourceBundle.getBundle <
                new Locale("zh", "CN"));		      <
      }							      <
      catch (MissingResourceException e2)		      <
      {							      <
							      <
        // Now we are really in trouble.		      <
        // very bad, definitely very bad...not going to get v <
        throw new MissingResourceException(		      <
          "\u65e0\u6cd5\u88c5\u5165\u4efb\u4f55\u8d44\u6e90\u <
      }							      <
    }							      <
  }							      <
							      <
  /**							      <
   * Return the resource file suffic for the indicated locale <
   * For most locales, this will be based the language code.  <
   * for Chinese, we do distinguish between Taiwan and PRC    <
   *							      <
   * @param locale the locale				      <
   * @return an String suffix which canbe appended to a resou <
   */							      <
  private static final String getResourceSuffix(Locale locale <
  {							      <
							      <
    String suffix = "_" + locale.getLanguage();		      <
    String country = locale.getCountry();		      <
							      <
    if (country.equals("TW"))				      <
      suffix += "_" + country;				      <
							      <
    return suffix;					      <
  }							      <
